{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588470"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:08:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15145"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15145"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7833"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52259"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"2438"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for discussion of his prostate magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) results. He has an elevated prostate specific antigen of 6.2 ng/mL (0-4.0). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination reveals a smooth, firm prostate with no nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) system is a structured reporting scheme for evaluating the likelihood of clinically significant prostate cancer using multiparametric MRI. Understanding the correct risk stratification for each score is crucial for clinical decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the correct description?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["PI-RADS 1: clinically significant cancer highly unlikely","PI-RADS 2: clinically significant cancer likely","PI-RADS 3: clinically significant cancer highly likely","PI-RADS 4: clinically significant cancer very highly likely","PI-RADS 5: clinically significant cancer equivocal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPI-RADS 1\u003C/strong\u003E correctly indicates that clinically significant cancer is highly unlikely. This represents the lowest risk category and typically does not require further investigation if clinical factors align.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPI-RADS 2\u003C/strong\u003E actually indicates that clinically significant cancer is unlikely, not likely as stated in the option. This represents low risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPI-RADS 3\u003C/strong\u003E indicates that the presence of clinically significant cancer is equivocal, not highly likely as stated in the option. This intermediate risk category often requires careful consideration of other clinical factors to determine management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPI-RADS 4\u003C/strong\u003E indicates that clinically significant cancer is likely, not very highly likely as stated in the option. This represents high risk and typically warrants biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPI-RADS 5\u003C/strong\u003E indicates that clinically significant cancer is very likely, not equivocal as stated in the option. This represents the highest risk category and almost always requires biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct interpretation of PI-RADS scores is essential for risk stratification and subsequent management decisions. The system helps standardise reporting and facilitates communication between radiologists and clinicians.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["PI-RADS (Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System) is a standardised reporting system for prostate MRI with scores from 1-5","PI-RADS 3 indicates intermediate risk where clinically significant cancer is equivocal","PI-RADS 4 indicates high (not very high) probability of clinically significant cancer"],"references":["Weinreb JC, Barentsz JO, Choyke PL, Cornud F, Haider MA, Macura KJ, Margolis D, Schnall MD, Shtern F, Tempany CM, Thoeny HC, Verma S. PI-RADS Prostate Imaging - Reporting and Data System: 2015, Version 2. Eur Urol. 2016 Jan;69(1):16-40. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2015.08.052. Epub 2015 Oct 1. PMID: 26427566; PMCID: PMC6467207.","Wen J, Liu W, Shen X, Hu W. PI-RADS v2.1 and PSAD for the prediction of clinically significant prostate cancer among patients with PSA levels of 4-10 ng/ml. Sci Rep. 2024 Mar 19;14(1):6570. doi: 10.1038/s41598-024-57337-y. PMID: 38503972; PMCID: PMC10951302.","Ahdoot M, Lebastchi AH, Long L, Wilbur AR, Gomella PT, Mehralivand S, Daneshvar MA, Yerram NK, O\u0027Connor LP, Wang AZ, Gurram S, Bloom J, Siddiqui MM, Linehan WM, Merino M, Choyke PL, Pinsky P, Parnes H, Shih JH, Turkbey B, Wood BJ, Pinto PA; Trio Study Group. Using Prostate Imaging-Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) Scores to Select an Optimal Prostate Biopsy Method: A Secondary Analysis of the Trio Study. Eur Urol Oncol. 2022 Apr;5(2):176-186. doi: 10.1016/j.euo.2021.03.004. Epub 2021 Apr 10. PMID: 33846112; PMCID: PMC9346635."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52259"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15145"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52259"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T14:56:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T14:57:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7833"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links